---
Midgaard's Guard Command treats the Reliquary Host as a cautionary precedent: a martial body defined by the institution it protects rather than independent law becomes that institution's enforcement arm.
The Guard Command's doctrine-loyalty principle, from the Compact of the Seven Chains, is supposed to prevent this — officers are bound to Knight doctrine above institutional instruction.
The Reckoning faction argues this principle was not applied during the Violet Compact's sealed warrant operations, making Guard Command of that period operationally equivalent to the Reliquary Host.
The Continuity faction disputes the parallel but has not produced the relevant sealed warrant operation records to contest it.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Wardens of Iron maintain safeguards specifically designed to prevent the Reliquary Host failure mode: a martial body converted from external defense to internal suppression when institutional leaders face accountability challenges.
The Night of Unsounded Bells' documented failure chain — bells silenced, Reliquary units reassigned from outer defense to internal suppression, archive partitioned — is cited in the Warden of Iron's emergency protocol framework as the canonical example.
The Warden of Iron's charter explicitly prohibits reassignment of external defense units to internal suppression without full multi-bloc authorization under the Neon Covenant's emergency framework.
The prohibition was introduced after the Jade Magistracy's analysis of the Gloamvault collapse.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's founding charter requires that the institution's security forces cannot be directed by the same body that controls access to the institution's records.
This clause was drafted in explicit response to the Reliquary Host model: when the martial body protecting an archive is directed by the office controlling archive access, it becomes a suppression tool.
The Synod-Scriptorium-Host interdependency at Kel'Shadra was the documented proof case.
Kiess's governance separates the functions: the Archive Hall's guards answer to the Syndic Council collectively, not to the archivist office.
The obsidian disc from the Kiess foundation excavations bears a Reliquary Host seal alongside the Synod intake mark — confirming Host authority was involved in the Spirebound Conclave's condemned-debtor transfer intake processing.

flags RAKUEN
---
The Reliquary Host's presence in Rakuen was the witnessing office's security detail — physical enforcement ensuring testimonies submitted to the Rakuen Bell Synod satellite office did not leave with the witness intact.
Rakuen's Garden Ledger contains entries describing individuals who submitted testimony to the witnessing office and were subsequently reported as unavailable, relocated, or deceased without family notification.
The pattern is consistent with Host operation: secure the testimony, secure the witness's silence.
The Garden Ledger Clerks cannot directly attribute these outcomes to Host action without access to the Rakuen witnessing office's security records, which are in the sealed Interface Galleries.
Rakuen's formal access request includes specific reference to the Host's operational records for the Rakuen witnessing period.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw has encountered Reliquary Host remnants in maritime contexts twice: once when a cargo manifest referenced "Host-certified relics" requiring oath-validation, and once when a ship arriving from Kel'Shadra-proximate waters carried a Host-sealed chest the Swift Court was asked to adjudicate.
The Shrine's position on Host-certified relics: Host certification establishes chain of custody within the Kel'Shadra institutional framework, not authentication of the relic's nature or legal status under current law.
Host-sealed materials require full independent assessment before any commercial or legal claim based on them is recognized.
The second case — the sealed chest — was opened by court order and found to contain testimony records, admitted as historical evidence only; no binding legal effect was assigned to their classifications.

flags MIDGAARD KHENARI
---
Khenari mortuary jurisprudence identifies the Reliquary Host's Sepulcher Compact as a fundamental violation of death-record law.
Under Khenari legal framework, death initiates the legal threshold process: debts settled, inheritance transferred, ongoing legal personhood converted to an estate.
The Sepulcher Compact's oath-bonded undead officers exist in legal impossibility: dead for purposes of inheritance law but alive for purposes of command authority.
No Khenari court would recognize command decisions made by Sepulcher officers after their death because the authority to make those decisions transferred to the estate at death.
The Host's attempt to use death as an administrative continuity tool inverts the legal framework death is supposed to trigger.

